answers.body_markdown:
The reason is that for deleting an object, Hibernate requires that the object is in persistent state. Thus, Hibernate first fetches the object (SELECT) and then removes it (DELETE).

Why Hibernate needs to fetch the object first? The reason is that Hibernate interceptors might be enabled (https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/orm/3.3/reference/en/html/events.html), and the object must be passed through these interceptors to complete its lifecycle. If rows are deleted directly in the database, the interceptor won&#39;t run.

On the other hand, it&#39;s possible to delete entities in one single SQL DELETE statement using bulk operations:

    Query q = session.createQuery(&quot;delete Entity where id = X&quot;);
    q.executeUpdate();

instead of using 

&gt; session.delete(object)

 
use

    getHibernateTemplate().delete(object)

In both place for `select`   query and also for `delete` use `getHibernateTemplate()`

In `select` query you have to use `DetachedCriteria` or `Criteria`

Example for select query

    List&lt;foo&gt; fooList = new ArrayList&lt;foo&gt;();
    DetachedCriteria queryCriteria = DetachedCriteria.forClass(foo.class);
    queryCriteria.add(Restrictions.eq(&quot;Column_name&quot;,restriction));
    fooList = getHibernateTemplate().findByCriteria(queryCriteria);

In hibernate avoid use of session,here I am not sure but problem occurs just because of session use

You can use `EntityManager` class. It is central interface for interacting with the persistence context and managing entity instances. It provides methods for CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations.  

`entityManager.getReference` method is used to obtain a reference to the Object entity with the specified id. The getReference method is commonly used to obtain a lightweight proxy of an entity without immediately fetching its data from the database. This is useful for deletion operations, as it avoids unnecessary data retrieval.

By using `entityManager.remove`, you instruct the `JPA` provider (such as Hibernate) to schedule the deletion of the entity during the next flush or commit operation. The `JPA` provider will then generate the appropriate `SQL DELETE` statement to remove the entity from the database.

     
    

    import jakarta.persistence.EntityManager;
    import jakarta.persistence.PersistenceContext;

    @Repository
    public class SampleRepositoryImpl {
    
        @PersistenceContext
        private EntityManager entityManager;
        
    ...
    
        @Override
        public void delete(int id) {
            entityManager.remove(entityManager.getReference(Employee.class,id));
        }
       
    }

